<article>
	<header>
	<h1><a href="http://foodsense.is/blog/lynns-monologue">Meet Lynn: &#8220;I can’t change everyone. But, I can tell them what I know.&#8221;</a></h1>
		</header>
		
	<div class="group">
		<img src="http://foodsense.is/uploads/post-images/Lynn_Butler_Photo.png" class="post-image border" alt="image" />			<p><em>What would a few minutes of driving behind a chicken truck mean for you? For Lynn and her husband, Marc, it planted a seed. A few weeks later, the image was alive in their minds when they confronted the realities of factory farming through a front page <a href="https://www.uta.edu/philosophy/faculty/burgess-jackson/Warrick,%20They%20Die%20Piece%20by%20Piece%20(2001).pdf">article</a> in The Washington Post. They immediately became vegetarian, (and eventually, vegan), and never looked back. Here, Lynn talks about lessons from her work on an animal sanctuary, adjusting to a vegetarian kitchen, and her evolving approach to sharing her choice with others.</em></p>
		<p><a href="http://foodsense.is/blog/lynns-monologue">Continue reading &raquo;</a></p>	</div>
		
	<footer>
		<ul>
			<li class="date"><time datetime="2011-07-27T09:00-05:00" pubdate><span>2011</span> <em>Jul 27</em></time></li>
